Enterprise Data Management: Pagination & LINQ Architecture
Project: FinancialSolution API
Module: Transaction History

Part 1: The PagedResult Pattern
When building enterprise APIs, returning massive datasets (like a user with 10,000 transactions) all at once will crash your server, drain the user's data, and freeze the frontend. The solution is the Paginated Response.

Instead of sending the entire dataset, you send a single "Page" of data wrapped in a custom PagedResult class that contains the exact metadata the frontend needs to render its tables.

The C# Implementation
C#
public async Task<PagedResult<TransactionHistoryResponse>> GetTransactionHistoryAsync(
    Guid customerId, int page, int pageSize)
{
    // 1. Fetch exactly one page of data
    var transactions = await _transactionRepository.GetWalletTransactionsAsync(wallet.Id, page, pageSize);

    // 2. Fetch the total count of all records
    var totalCount = await _transactionRepository.GetTransactionCountAsync(wallet.Id);

    // 3. Return the packaged response
    return new PagedResult<TransactionHistoryResponse>
    {
        Items = transactions.Select(x => new TransactionHistoryResponse
        {
            Amount = x.Amount,
            TransactionType = x.TransactionType.ToString(),
            Status = x.Status.ToString(),
            Reference = x.Reference,
            CreatedAt = x.CreatedAt
        }).ToList(),
        
        Page = page,
        PageSize = pageSize,
        TotalCount = totalCount
    };
}
The JSON Output
When this hits the frontend (React, Next.js, etc.), the JSON is perfectly structured to build a Data Table component with pagination buttons:

JSON
{
  "items": [
    { "amount": 5000, "type": "Credit", "status": "Success" },
    { "amount": 1000, "type": "Debit", "status": "Success" }
  ],
  "page": 1,
  "pageSize": 10,
  "totalCount": 10000
}
Part 2: The Core LINQ Toolkit
To actually fetch that single page of data efficiently, the Infrastructure Layer relies on five core Entity Framework LINQ methods. These methods translate C# directly into highly optimized SQL queries.

CountAsync(): Asks the database exactly how many rows match a rule, without downloading the rows. Prevents server crashes when calculating page numbers.

Skip(x): Tells SQL to completely ignore the first x rows it finds.

Take(y): Tells SQL to grab the next y rows, and then immediately stop searching.
(Example: To get Page 3 with 10 items per page, use Skip(20).Take(10)).

Select(): Acts as a factory assembly line. It loops through heavy database entities and transforms them into lightweight C# DTOs, stripping away sensitive data.

ToListAsync(): The executioner. Skip, Take, and Select only prepare a query in memory. ToListAsync() actually fires the query to the database, downloads the results, and packages them into a C# List.